The following are major news items in leading Israeli newspapers on Tuesday. Ha'aretz: -- The Jerusalem Magistrate's Court Monday acquitted Shin Bet security service recruit Avishai Raviv of charges that he failed to prevent the assassination of former prime minister Yitzhak Rabin. The court ruled there was no evidence that Raviv knew assassin Yigal Amir was plotting to kill Rabin. -- The Iraqis may be hiding surface-to-surface missiles (SSMs) or prohibited chemical or biological weapons in Syria in an attempt to evade detection by American forces, Israeli Brigadier General Yossi Kuperwasser told the Knesset (Parliament) Defense and Foreign Affairs Committee on Monday. The Jerusalem Post: -- Israeli Foreign Minister Silvan Shalom met with US President George W. Bush and the American foreign policy team on Monday to discuss the release of the "road map" to Middle East peace. -- Despite reports that the United States is pressing Israel to make "gestures" to the Palestinian National Authority to strengthen new Prime Minister Mahmoud Abbas, Israel will not increase the amount of money it will transfer to the PNA in April. Enditem 